        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net&gt;</ph> classes use the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) to encrypt the connection for several network protocols.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For http connections, the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net.WebRequest&gt;</ph> and <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Net.WebResponse&gt;</ph> classes use SSL to communicate with web hosts that support SSL.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The decision to use SSL is made by the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net.WebRequest&gt;</ph> class, based on the URI it is given.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>If the URI begins with "https:", SSL is used; if the URI begins with "http:", an unencrypted connection is used.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>To use SSL with File Transfer Protocol (FTP), set the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net.FtpWebRequest.EnableSsl&gt;</ph> property to true prior to calling <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Net.FtpWebRequest.GetResponse&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Similarly, to use SSL with Simple Mail Transport Protocol (SMTP), set the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net.Mail.SmtpClient.EnableSsl&gt;</ph> property to true prior to sending the email.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net.Security.SslStream&gt;</ph> class provides a stream-based abstraction for SSL, and offers many ways to configure the SSL handshake.</source>
        </trans-unit>
